19:52.258 --> 19:55.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The president
met this afternoon
at the State Department with
members of his

19:55.961 --> 19:59.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
national security team to
discuss the fight
against ISIS and the state of
the larger war

19:59.832 --> 20:05.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Syria, as a key deadline
approaches tomorrow
for a cessation of hostilities.

20:05.037 --> 20:06.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He spoke to reporters moments
ago.

20:06.872 --> 20:10.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
And none of us are under any
illusions. We're

20:10.910 --> 20:15.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all aware of the many potential
pitfalls.
And there are plenty of reasons
for skepticism.

20:15.781 --> 20:22.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But history would judge us
harshly if we didn't
do our part in at least trying
to end this

20:22.455 --> 20:26.892 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
terrible conflict with
diplomacy. If implemented
-- and that's a significant if
-- the cessation

20:26.926 --> 20:34.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
could reduce the violence and
get more food
and aid to Syrians who are
suffering and desperately

20:34.700 --> 20:36.602 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
need it.

20:36.635 --> 20:41.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It could save lives.
Potentially, it could
also lead to negotiations on a
political settlement

20:41.707 --> 20:46.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to end the civil war, so that
everybody can
focus their attention on
destroying ISIL.

20:46.479 --> 20:50.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why the United States
will do everything
we can to maximize the chances
of success

20:50.983 --> 20:52.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in this cessation of
hostilities.

20:52.818 --> 20:57.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, what are
the realities
for a potential halt to some of
the violence

20:57.423 --> 20:59.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and delivery of much-needed aid
in Syria?

20:59.091 --> 21:00.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret
Warner reports.

21:00.960 --> 21:04.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: There were
definitely mixed
signals of progress before
tomorrow's midnight

21:04.130 --> 21:08.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cease-fire deadline in Syria.
Aid trucks rolled
into the rebel-held Damascus
suburb of Ghouta

21:08.134 --> 21:10.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
yesterday, long besieged by the
Assad regime.

21:10.269 --> 21:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in Syria's east, a U.N.
airdrop of food
went awry. Earlier in the week,
Russia claimed

21:15.441 --> 21:17.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's pared back bombing against
U.S.-backed
rebels.

21:17.576 --> 21:21.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAJ. GEN. IGOR KONASHENKOV,
Russian Ministry
of Defense (through translator):
Russian aviation

21:21.247 --> 21:25.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
performs no strikes in these
regions where
we have received or are
continuing to receive

21:25.918 --> 21:27.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
claims to cease the fire and
start negotiations.

21:27.686 --> 21:30.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But, today,
there were reports
of Russian bombing of rebel-held
areas in

21:30.789 --> 21:33.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Syria's northwest and regime
bombing in a
suburb of Damascus.

21:33.058 --> 21:36.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The last-ditch agreement,
brokered Monday
by the U.S. and Russia, called
for a -- quote

21:36.896 --> 21:40.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- "cessation of hostilities."
It exempts
operations against ISIS, the
al-Qaida linked

21:40.666 --> 21:43.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jabhat al-Nusra, and terror
groups on a U.N.
list.

21:44.003 --> 21:49.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The Syrian government of
President Bashar
Assad has signed on, as have
some rebel groups.

21:49.575 --> 21:54.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the major Saudi-backed
opposition group
said it would commit to just two
weeks.

21:54.947 --> 22:01.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SALEM AL MESLET, High
Negotiations Committee:
To be frank with you, we do not
trust Russia,

22:01.887 --> 22:04.790 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we do not trust this regime.

22:04.823 --> 22:08.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And U.S. ally
Turkey said
it wants to continue hitting
Syrian Kurds

22:08.761 --> 22:10.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
linked to Turkey's Kurdish
terrorists.

22:10.696 --> 22:15.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The day after it was announced,
in Washington,
senators pressed Secretary of
State John Kerry.

22:15.434 --> 22:17.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: I just hope it's not a
rope-a-dope
deal.

22:17.670 --> 22:19.438 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

22:19.471 --> 22:23.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KERRY, U.S. Secretary of
State: Well,
it may be. I'm not going to
vouch for this.

22:23.309 --> 22:28.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not going to say this
process is sure
to work, because I don't know.
But I know

22:28.847 --> 22:34.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that this is the best way to try
to end the
war, and it's the only
alternative before

22:34.954 --> 22:37.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
us, if indeed we're going to
have a political
settlement.

22:37.590 --> 22:40.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Many Syria
experts are skeptical
too. Robert Ford, former
ambassador to Syria,

22:40.626 --> 22:46.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resigned in 2014 over the
president's refusal
to arm the Syrian rebels. Now a
fellow with

22:46.498 --> 22:49.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Middle East Institute in
Washington, he
also teaches at Yale.

22:49.935 --> 22:54.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT FORD, Former U.S.
Ambassador to Syria:
Secretary Kerry has made huge,
huge, huge

22:54.273 --> 23:00.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
efforts, but it's too early to
say if it represents
any progress. The cease-fire is
going to be

23:00.980 --> 23:06.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a huge uphill. The Russians and
the Syrian
regime have incentives to keep
fighting. I

23:06.919 --> 23:10.289 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
don't think the war is over by
any means.

23:10.322 --> 23:15.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But Prem Kumar,
who worked
on Syria on the National
Security Council

23:15.894 --> 23:19.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
until last year, says it's an
important first
step.

23:19.064 --> 23:23.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PREM KUMAR, Former National
Security Council
Member: It is an important
process that will

23:23.636 --> 23:28.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hopefully lead to increased
humanitarian assistance,
and then, longer term, if the
process holds,

23:28.140 --> 23:29.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to discussions about the
longer-term political
issues that have bedeviled Syria
for several

23:29.908 --> 23:31.710 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
years now.

23:31.744 --> 23:32.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: He thinks it
marks a welcome
evolution in U.S. thinking, away
from regime

23:32.945 --> 23:34.580 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
change.

23:34.613 --> 23:37.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PREM KUMAR: What is really
important about
this recent initiative is that I
think it

23:37.416 --> 23:43.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
begins to shift from one in
which the U.S.
and its partners were trying to
increase pressure

23:43.922 --> 23:45.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on Assad to negotiate his own
departure to
trying to freeze the conflict,
provide humanitarian

23:45.791 --> 23:49.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
assistance, and set up a process
to address
the longer-term political
issues.

23:49.295 --> 23:53.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: What has caused
that shift?
The sudden insertion of Russian
bombers and

23:53.599 --> 23:55.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
advisers late last September.

23:55.534 --> 23:58.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through
translator): The only right way
to fight international

23:58.904 --> 24:03.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terrorism in Syria and on the
territory of
the states neighboring it is to
act preemptively.

24:03.809 --> 24:08.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: For months, as
Secretary
Kerry negotiated for a Syria
peace process

24:08.881 --> 24:13.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with Russia's foreign minister,
Russian bombers
were dramatically tilting the
battlefield.

24:13.519 --> 24:16.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Five months ago, the rebels were
gaining ground.

24:16.455 --> 24:21.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now Assad's forces have retaken
key areas
in the west and surrounded
Aleppo, Syria's

24:21.060 --> 24:26.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
largest city. And the Islamic
State has expanded
in the east. Ford sees Russia,
along with

24:26.565 --> 24:31.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iran, Turkey and Saudi Arabia,
all backing
different fighting elements, as
exerting far

24:31.704 --> 24:34.039 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more leverage now than the U.S.

24:34.073 --> 24:39.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FORD: Russia absolutely
is in the driver's
seat, and the Americans are
watching the car

24:39.678 --> 24:43.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drive by. The Americans are
becoming basically
irrelevant.

24:43.515 --> 24:52.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Former French
Foreign Minister
Laurent Fabius said the U.S.
lost credibility

24:52.791 --> 24:59.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when it didn't follow through on
the President
Obama's threat to strike Syria
for using chemical

24:59.732 --> 25:03.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
weapons in 2013. He added, "One
doesn't get
the sense that there is a very
strong commitment.

25:03.969 --> 25:06.772 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And obviously the Iranians and
Russians feel
that."

25:06.805 --> 25:11.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Indeed, Mr. Obama repeatedly
resisted calls
to arm moderate rebel groups, as
he explained

25:11.677 --> 25:21.120 align:left position:37.5%,start line:86.67% size:62.5%
to
The New York Times in 2014.

25:21.153 --> 25:27.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA: It has always been
a fantasy,
this idea that we could provide
some light

25:27.092 --> 25:33.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
arms or even more sophisticated
arms to what
was essentially an opposition
made up of former

25:33.065 --> 25:35.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doctors, farmers, pharmacists
and so forth.

25:35.934 --> 25:42.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Mr. Obama's
aides say he
feared arming inexperienced
rebels would draw

25:42.207 --> 25:49.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the U.S. down a slippery slope
of deeper military
involvement. But Ford says the
president's

25:49.415 --> 25:51.283 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
unwillingness did just that.

25:51.316 --> 25:58.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FORD: I think that their
inaction put
us on a slippery slope. Frankly,
we now have

25:58.624 --> 26:03.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American military personnel
operating in Syria,
Margaret. None of us wanted that
in 2011,

26:03.695 --> 26:07.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 2012, in 2013. But now we're
flying combat
operations against the Islamic
State, not

26:07.399 --> 26:10.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Syrians taking care of it,
Americans having
to help Syrians take care of it.

26:10.202 --> 26:16.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And, in fact,
the administration
is now asking Congress for
additional funds

26:16.942 --> 26:23.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for those operations. So, what
happens if
this cease-fire fails? On
Tuesday, Kerry hinted

26:23.482 --> 26:25.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that deeper military aid could
be forthcoming.

26:25.951 --> 26:32.558 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN KERRY: There is a
significant discussion
taking place now about plan B in
the event

26:32.591 --> 26:35.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that we don't succeed at the
table.

26:35.060 --> 26:38.530 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARGARET WARNER: Foreign
Relations Committee
Chair Bob Corker was dubious.

26:38.564 --> 26:44.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. BOB CORKER (R), Tennessee:
There is no
plan B. Russia knows there will
be no plan

26:44.636 --> 26:46.371 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
B.

26:46.405 --> 26:50.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT FORD: I saw Secretary
Kerry talk about
plan B. That's nice. We will see
if there's

26:50.843 --> 26:52.778 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
anything there.

26:52.811 --> 26:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Kumar said
there is the possibility
of giving the rebels more
powerful weaponry

26:57.349 --> 27:03.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or creating safe-zones inside
Syria. But even
he doubts how much more the
president will

27:03.822 --> 27:06.325 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
do in his remaining 11 months.

27:06.358 --> 27:12.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PREM KUMAR: I think it is
unlikely that the
administration is going to do a
180-degree

27:12.498 --> 27:18.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
turn in its policy on Syria, but
I think if
the president begins to believe
that there

27:18.704 --> 27:26.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is progress in sight, and that
the U.S. needs
to do more in order to achieve
an end to the

27:26.745 --> 27:30.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conflict, then I think he would
be willing
to consider it.

27:30.349 --> 27:34.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: A long road
ahead that depends
heavily on what happens this
weekend.

27:34.953 --> 27:37.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

27:37.256 --> 27:38.957 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

27:38.991 --> 27:43.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": how
the mother
of Columbine shooter Dylan
Klebold came to

27:43.262 --> 27:47.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terms with her son's actions;
the tunnels
that house Tijuana's homeless;
and a poet's

27:47.232 --> 27:49.835 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
take on the popular term black
girl magic.

27:49.868 --> 27:55.040 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, first, the economic
recovery may be well
into its sixth year, and the
jobless rate

27:55.073 --> 27:58.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is at its lowest point since
2008. Even so,
it's clear many Americans still
feel plenty

27:58.977 --> 28:04.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of anxiety, either about their
job, their
income, their finances or what
may be happening

28:04.783 --> 28:06.552 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to their quality of life.

28:06.585 --> 28:10.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman dives
deeper into what's behind that
with the first

28:10.455 --> 28:14.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of two conversations he has on
this subject.
This one features a liberal
perspective, part

28:14.660 --> 28:17.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of our weekly series Making
Sense, which airs
every Thursday on the
"NewsHour."

