28:25.804 --> 28:28.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We're going to
build a big,
beautiful wall.

28:28.473 --> 28:34.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (VT-I),
Presidential Candidate:
There is nothing we cannot
accomplish.

28:34.313 --> 28:39.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Another story on
Trump and Sanders
as political outliers defining
this year's

28:39.885 --> 28:40.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
presidential campaign?

28:40.919 --> 28:43.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We're in first
place everywhere.

28:43.255 --> 28:49.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But why have they
taken America
by storm? We put that question
to longtime

28:49.995 --> 28:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
liberal thinker Robert Reich,
friend of Hillary
Clinton since college, secretary
of labor

28:55.434 --> 28:59.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under her husband, Bill, but now
a Bernie
Sanders supporter.

28:59.605 --> 29:05.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you surprised by the turn
America has
taken politically in the last
half-year?

29:05.077 --> 29:11.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT REICH, Former U.S. Labor
Secretary:
I'm surprised at how fast it
happened. I predicted

29:11.883 --> 29:20.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in my book "Saving Capitalism"
that the biggest
political contest in the future
would be between,

29:20.726 --> 29:24.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not Democrats and Republicans,
but between
the anti-establishment populists
and the establishment,

29:24.663 --> 29:32.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because I saw the increase in
this degree
of anxious class, I call it,
anger and frustration

29:32.104 --> 29:35.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the economy and society are
no longer
working for them.

29:35.941 --> 29:41.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Covering economic
developments
in America since the 1970s, I
too have been

29:41.346 --> 29:44.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chronicling this growing anxiety
my entire
career.

29:44.483 --> 29:48.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I met security guard Bobby Hicks
five years
ago.

29:48.487 --> 29:54.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOBBY HICKS, Security Guard: I
am the most
insecure security officer you
will meet, because

29:54.359 --> 29:57.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm worried. Right now, I live
paycheck to
paycheck.

29:57.062 --> 30:00.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Cookie Sheers is an
administrative
assistant at a Boston nonprofit.

30:00.265 --> 30:02.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COOKIE SHEERS, Administrative
Assistant: We
all feel stuck, like you're just
at that edge

30:02.100 --> 30:07.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
