Six months after the tragedy,
when I was finally

41:54.011 --> 42:04.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shown the evidence at the
sheriff's department,
and we saw things such as the
basement tapes,

42:04.422 --> 42:10.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we saw photographs of some of
their weapons,
I remember being -- feeling just
ill.

42:10.495 --> 42:20.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I stood up and thought I was
going to be sick.
I -- it was such a shock to me,
because it

42:20.938 --> 42:27.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't make sense that the child
that I loved
could actually be doing those
things or could

42:27.245 --> 42:32.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have planned to do those things.
And, for
me, that was almost the
beginning of grief

42:32.383 --> 42:38.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all over again, because I had to
grieve for
a different human being than I
had loved before.

42:38.656 --> 42:43.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You focus later
on, on the
suicide aspect to this, not
pushing aside

42:43.494 --> 42:47.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the murder aspect, but the
suicide of your
own son, which really forces and
focuses the

42:47.899 --> 42:49.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
issue on depression.

42:49.700 --> 42:55.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, explain that. What, in the
end, do you
-- what, in the end, do you
think led him

42:55.039 --> 42:56.808 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to commit these atrocities?

42:56.841 --> 43:00.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUE KLEBOLD: I think, when we
look at suicide,
and we look at murder-suicide as
one small

43:00.978 --> 43:08.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
subset of suicidal acts, we have
to understand
that this is a very complex
issue, that there

43:08.886 --> 43:12.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are no simple answers or simple
reasons or
explanations.

43:12.657 --> 43:18.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The things that occur for
someone to experience
that level of suicidality, they
are things

43:18.863 --> 43:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
such as biological factors,
genetic factors,
environmental factors, both the
home, the

43:22.834 --> 43:26.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
school, the culture, personality
factors,
and also triggering factors,
such as events

43:26.537 --> 43:31.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that occur, losses, bullying,
arrests. And
it is all of those things
working together

43:31.175 --> 43:33.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
operating for that one
vulnerable person.

43:33.177 --> 43:38.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when someone begins to
deteriorate, when
their thoughts are becoming
suicidal, they

43:38.749 --> 43:45.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are in the process of losing
access to their
own tools of self-governments,
of conscience,

43:45.256 --> 43:47.024 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of reason.

43:47.058 --> 43:50.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they reach a state where
they are not
thinking the way the rest of us
are thinking,

43:50.995 --> 43:56.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if we are healthy. They don't
have the same
decision points. And I believe
that Dylan's

43:56.601 --> 44:04.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
brain health was the reason that
he was involved.
He wasn't able to act in a way
that he would

44:04.942 --> 44:07.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have if he were not unwell.

44:07.445 --> 44:12.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You write often
here of the
victims, of their families, of
the pain that

44:12.917 --> 44:15.052 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you have felt from the
beginning.

44:15.086 --> 44:19.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're donating your profits, I
understand,
from the book to charitable
organizations

44:19.423 --> 44:24.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that look at mental health
issues. But why
write the book at all? Why in
the first place?

44:24.428 --> 44:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know that, from the moment
this happened
until now, people wonder about
you, wonder

44:25.863 --> 44:29.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about -- probably wonder now
about the motives
in writing the book.

44:29.300 --> 44:31.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why did you want to do it?

44:31.669 --> 44:38.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUE KLEBOLD: The reasons for me,
I think,
were primarily because people
who knew me

44:38.409 --> 44:45.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or knew Dylan or knew our story
would give
me feedback that they were
affected, that

44:45.082 --> 44:47.385 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
their parenting changed because
of this.

44:47.418 --> 44:53.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had met an individual, among
many individuals,
one who had problems with a
youngster who

44:53.658 --> 45:00.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was 13, and her daughter acted a
little bit
different, a little bit more
withdrawn. And

45:00.798 --> 45:07.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the mother told me, "Because I
know you and
because I know that kids can
hide things and

45:07.405 --> 45:13.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of the things that they
hide can be lethal,"
she explored. She dug into the
kid's life,

45:13.878 --> 45:19.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asked her daughter repeatedly
and in depth,
and finally was able to learn
from her daughter

45:19.884 --> 45:25.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that she had been raped while
she had left
the house once when she wasn't
supposed to.

45:25.456 --> 45:31.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I feel that we all have --
the most important
thing we can do is accept the
concept that

45:31.495 --> 45:38.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
someone we love may not be
feeling inside
the way they present to us, and
that is a

45:38.703 --> 45:42.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
responsibility we have as
parents and family
members to try to help them, to
try to elicit

45:42.607 --> 45:46.110 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from them what they're
experiencing and to
-- and if we do learn that they
are having

45:46.143 --> 45:51.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
suicidal thoughts or other
thoughts that are
symptomatic of illness, to get
them help.

45:51.916 --> 45:53.384 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

45:53.417 --> 45:58.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The book is "A Mother's
Reckoning: Living
in the Aftermath of Tragedy."

45:58.222 --> 45:59.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sue Klebold. Thank you very
much.

45:59.457 --> 46:01.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SUE KLEBOLD: Thank you.

46:01.325 --> 46:04.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Among the
homeless population
in Tijuana, Mexico, are migrants
on the way

46:04.228 --> 46:11.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the U.S. And because of
police raids, they're
living in a rival canal, hiding
in the canal's

46:11.035 --> 46:12.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
branching tunnels.

46:12.937 --> 46:17.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KPBS Fronteras reporter Jean
Guerrero went
inside the tunnels to learn
about the struggles

46:17.942 --> 46:19.210 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
these migrants face.

46:19.243 --> 46:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A warning: Some of the images in
this story
may be disturbing.

46:23.547 --> 46:28.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Jose Alberto
Zavala is one
of hundreds of migrants living
inside the

46:28.352 --> 46:32.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tijuana River Canal's tunnels.
He says he
doesn't feel safe anywhere else.

46:32.490 --> 46:37.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE ALBERTO ZAVALA, Migrant
(through translator):
They see us outside and the
police pick us

46:37.962 --> 46:39.764 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

46:39.797 --> 46:44.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Zavala is known
as Chapo, like
the Mexican drug lord, because
of his short

46:44.402 --> 46:49.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stature. But the similarities
pretty much
end there. He recently rescued
this cat from

46:49.240 --> 46:51.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the side of the road.

46:51.042 --> 46:55.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE ALBERTO ZAVALA (through
translator):
She's a girl. The other day, I
banged myself

46:55.813 --> 46:59.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up because the police were
trying to put me
in one of the rehab centers. But
that's a

46:59.884 --> 47:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kidnapping. What they do is a
violation of
human rights.

47:05.389 --> 47:10.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: For years,
Tijuana's homeless
were living out in the open, in
makeshift

47:10.961 --> 47:14.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tents in a Tijuana River Canal
encampment
known as El Bordo.

47:14.432 --> 47:17.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, last spring, the municipal
government
evacuated the encampment,
placing hundreds

47:17.902 --> 47:22.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of people into rehab centers,
many against
their will. Officials say the
migrants were

47:22.339 --> 47:26.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hurting tourism and committing
crimes. Many
were using heroin or
methamphetamine after

47:26.110 --> 47:29.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
being deported from the U.S.,
where they had
families and jobs.

47:29.480 --> 47:35.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some, like Chapo, say they don't
do drugs
at all, but were sent to rehab
anyway. Since

47:35.453 --> 47:39.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then, hundreds have escaped or
were released
from these facilities. They're
now hiding

47:40.024 --> 47:46.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the storm drains. Police
sometimes track
them down and place them back in
rehab. Others

47:46.397 --> 47:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are taken to jail or put on
buses out of town.

47:49.934 --> 47:56.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Police raids of the canal are
sometimes proving
fatal. The canal is flanked by
Tijuana's busiest

47:56.440 --> 48:02.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
highways, and when the migrants
run from the
police, some are killed by cars
speeding past.

48:02.913 --> 48:08.152 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just last month, at least two
were killed
trying to escape police.

48:08.185 --> 48:14.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chapo has erected memorial
wooden crosses
for several friends he says he
lost during

48:14.225 --> 48:15.860 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
police raids.

48:15.893 --> 48:20.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE ALBERTO ZAVALA (through
translator):
The 18th, also chapitas, and the
guy from

48:20.197 --> 48:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Oaxaca. But I don't know why.

48:22.566 --> 48:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Chapo says the
police sometimes
arrest migrants when they're
just standing

48:27.671 --> 48:33.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the street, trying to find
work in construction,
or washing car windshields with
dirty rags.

48:33.944 --> 48:41.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A migrant who called himself
Carlos Francisco
says he was run over by a car
while running

48:41.085 --> 48:48.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
across the highway during a
police raid two
days prior. He was injured so
badly, he couldn't

48:48.192 --> 48:49.693 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
walk.

48:49.727 --> 48:54.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says the police came while he
and his friends
were sleeping in the canal.

48:54.899 --> 48:59.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
come and grab
us. They -- they beat us.

48:59.303 --> 49:04.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Another man had a
large gash
on his head from where he says
police threw

49:04.842 --> 49:07.478 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him against the asphalt during
the same raid.

49:07.511 --> 49:13.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Tijuana's police chief,
Alejandro Lares, defends
his policy of flushing everybody
out of the

49:13.551 --> 49:19.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
canal. He says he is planning a
full-scale
clearing operation in the coming
weeks.

49:19.356 --> 49:22.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEJANDRO LARES VALLADARES,
Tijuana, Mexico,
Police Chief: We're going to
take over the

49:22.626 --> 49:24.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
whole ravine on Tijuana.

49:24.395 --> 49:27.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: The federal
government has
jurisdiction over the canal, but
the Tijuana

49:27.965 --> 49:30.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Police Department has permission
to patrol
the area.

49:30.801 --> 49:34.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEJANDRO LARES VALLADARES: It's
a no-man's
land. So, for that, it's easier
for them to

49:34.605 --> 49:37.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
buy drugs, sell drugs, and
obviously to consume
drugs.

49:37.908 --> 49:43.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Lares says he has
ordered 14
all-terrain vehicles to patrol
the canal.

49:43.047 --> 49:48.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He expects them to arrive any
day now. When
asked about alleged police
beatings, he says

49:48.619 --> 49:51.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
migrants should file complaints
so that he
can investigate.

49:51.088 --> 49:55.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEJANDRO LARES VALLADARES: I'm
not going
to tolerate any abuse from an
officer to a

49:55.826 --> 49:57.628 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
citizen.

49:57.661 --> 50:01.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Migrants say they
think filing
complaints would do them more
harm than good.

50:01.832 --> 50:04.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They fear being arrested if they
confront
police.

50:04.602 --> 50:09.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back in the tunnels, Chapo says
the current
strategy of removing migrants
from the canal

50:09.340 --> 50:15.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
makes life so hard for them,
they have no
choice but to turn to petty
crimes, which

50:15.379 --> 50:17.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can get them arrested. It's a
vicious cycle.

50:17.882 --> 50:22.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE ALBERTO ZAVALA (through
translator):
They kick you and say, you have
to come with

50:22.152 --> 50:27.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them. Why? Because you don't
have an I.D.
You shouldn't be sleeping here.
Where do you

50:27.157 --> 50:33.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want me to sleep if you don't
let me work?
If I go collect cans, you pick
me up. If I

50:33.998 --> 50:36.567 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go to the dumpster, you pick me
up.

50:36.600 --> 50:41.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: He doesn't think
Tijuana officials
will ever succeed in ridding the
city of homeless

50:41.605 --> 50:43.474 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
migrants.

50:43.507 --> 50:46.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE ALBERTO ZAVALA (through
translator):
This is the border. There will
always be migrants,

50:46.544 --> 50:48.312 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
always, always.

50:48.345 --> 50:52.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: But as police
raids of the
canal become more sophisticated
and frequent,

50:52.249 --> 50:54.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the tunnel dwellers face a
growing challenge.

50:54.718 --> 50:57.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jean
Guerrero
in Tijuana.

50:57.755 --> 51:03.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Next, we turn
to our year-long
series Race Matters.

51:03.494 --> 51:07.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, special correspondent
Charlayne Hunter-Gault
sits down with Bethann Hardison,
a former

51:07.398 --> 51:10.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
model and current owner of a New
York modeling
agency.

51:10.401 --> 51:15.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Hollywood comes under fire
for the lack
of diversity, Hardison shares
her solution

51:15.172 --> 51:17.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for making the fashion industry
more inclusive.

51:17.141 --> 51:22.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: For
generations, this
was the face of the fashion
industry, beautiful

51:22.546 --> 51:35.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
models in stunning designer
outfits, but that
face came to be almost always
white, with

51:35.960 --> 51:42.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a few notable exceptions, like
Naomi Campbell
and Iman.

51:42.866 --> 51:48.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Enter Bethann Hardison, herself
a former model,
who decided that just wasn't
good enough.

51:48.505 --> 51:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I caught up with her at her home
base in New
York City.

51:53.677 --> 51:56.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bethann Hardison, thank you for
joining us.

51:56.447 --> 52:00.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BETHANN HARDISON, Modeling
Agency Owner: Thank
you for having me.

52:00.417 --> 52:05.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: You
know, we have
seen all the beautiful models
like Beverly

52:05.723 --> 52:12.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Johnson, Iman, even yourself in
magazines
for many years, but there
weren't many of

52:12.730 --> 52:13.530 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

52:13.564 --> 52:16.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why was that? What was that
like?

52:16.166 --> 52:18.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BETHANN HARDISON: Well, there
were many back
in the day.

52:18.535 --> 52:23.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, back in the '70s and
'80s, there was
a great deal between runway and
print. And

52:23.741 --> 52:28.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then, by, say, 2000 -- well,
'80s and the
'90s, it was pretty good. And
then by '90,

52:28.245 --> 52:29.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mid-'90s, it just began to
disappear.

52:30.014 --> 52:32.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a change of the industry
because of
the Eastern European models
start to come

52:32.082 --> 52:33.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in. Things just changed. The
business changed.

52:33.851 --> 52:37.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: So, this
influx of
non-black people, non-women of
color really

52:37.688 --> 52:40.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
decimated the ranks of black
models on the
runway?

52:40.991 --> 52:46.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BETHANN HARDISON: It definitely
did. It changed
everything. And when they began
to bring in

52:46.497 --> 52:52.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more girls from outside, what
